WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:04.560
When you're in the weeds and you're just coding and looking at the UI,

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.360
you don't think about this is a life or death situation.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:27.040
When the vaccine stuff came around, I knew, do we have the right inventory at the right place

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:31.760
Distribution in West Virginia is managed by the National Guard, predominantly.

00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:36.160
You know, it wasn't as efficient as we would like, and we were aware of that,

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:39.119
but you know, we're in a pandemic, there's no playbook here.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:44.080
There were a lot of hands in different files, you know, they were working with Excel files.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:46.400
I knew we needed an advanced planning system.

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:51.520
And when major costs hit the ground, he shot me a text and he said, hey, we need a tool.

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:54.400
It wasn't even a question, of course we're going to do that.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:05.120
Distribution in West Virginia is managed by the National Guard, predominantly.

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:09.120
The project started with just giving them a more automated process

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:14.080
for different groups to submit the data that ultimately

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:18.800
gave them the information that they needed to develop their distribution plan.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:20.800
In our state, we have five distribution hubs.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.360
If you look at a map of West Virginia, you can basically touch

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:27.040
the four corners of the state, and you're going to find a hub,

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:28.720
and then there's a hub in Charleston.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.480
The key priorities were simplicity, right?

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:36.400
I mean, we got to have something where at hub level, at user level,

00:01:36.959 --> 00:01:40.000
they just have to log in, key in a number and hit enter.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.559
And we kind of looked at each other and said, we don't have time to build a database.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:50.080
We needed something that was cost effective, but that we could get it up and running quickly.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.720
We knew we'd get to a place where they wanted more visualization.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:54.160
These are government entities.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:55.839
There's not an open-ended checkbook.

00:01:55.839 --> 00:01:57.120
This is taxpayer money.

00:01:57.120 --> 00:01:59.120
We're like, what can do all of that for us?

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:04.320
So Shiny just became the quick and easy solution that came to mind for both of us.

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:15.360
We needed to create something that would ingest,

00:02:15.360 --> 00:02:18.479
had about 10 different people submitting every week,

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:22.320
and then aggregating that information into an output

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:25.119
that would allow them to make strategic decisions.

00:02:25.679 --> 00:02:30.960
The manual way, at best, we would get to that finished product Sunday night

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:33.839
and have to start operations Monday morning.

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:39.199
So we're now, we have that ready to go by 4 p.m. on Wednesday.

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:50.399
The reason we've been able to be successful, I think,

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:52.000
is because of this distribution network,

00:02:52.559 --> 00:02:55.119
knowing where these vaccines are going at any given point.

00:02:55.119 --> 00:02:56.960
You're going to run into some problems, right,

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.960
where you may not have the right quantities necessarily at the right place.

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:05.360
So that does require some, what we call, inner hub transfer, so to speak.

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:10.880
Based on the tool we built, we're able to provide visibility clear through this project.

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:13.759
And so we're seeing real-time draining of supply from the hubs.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:28.800
In combat, I'm moving fuel, ammunition, medical supplies,

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:31.119
maintenance repair parts.

00:03:31.119 --> 00:03:33.039
And there's this thing called the enemy out there

00:03:33.039 --> 00:03:35.919
trying to take you out while you're doing it, right?

00:03:36.479 --> 00:03:40.479
I've always taken the approach of if you can do it in that environment,

00:03:40.479 --> 00:03:43.839
you can do it in any environment minus the enemy.

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:45.679
Sometimes I have to tell myself, like,

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:48.399
no, it's actually a huge feat that we've accomplished all of this,

00:03:48.399 --> 00:03:52.000
because it just seems like we've all been doing our jobs.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.600
The entire principle behind this is build something in an agile manner

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:57.279
that you are going to repair day.

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:01.039
And the happiest day of this entire thing is going to be when you turn it off.

